	url = {https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-79951787406&partnerID=40&md5=6937b399a2b40fa18f63ac520beecce0},
	abstract = {The Indian government's proposal to spend more than $80 billion on procurement in 2011-15 will improve the prospects of the country's aerospace industrial growth strategy. This effort is also causing the industry to restructure, with streamlining efforts and consolidation, as businesses shift focus from serving the local market to emerging as leading global companies. The country's Defense Offsets Policy mandates that 30-50% of a contract total be reserved for the domestic aerospace industry. The government expects this effort will help aerospace companies to achieve a new level of industrial competence by expanding basic engineering skills and enabling companies to start delivering value-added products. The policy also permits commercial aviation to be tapped by suppliers to meet offset requirements. The market is expected to expand at a compound annual growth rate above 18% and Boeing forecasts delivery of 1,150 commercial aircrafts in the country in the next 20 years.},
